Package au.edu.anu.omhtk.rng

Class Pcg32

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.Random
      • au.edu.anu.omhtk.rng.Pcg32
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    public class Pcg32
extends java.util.Random

    Implementation of a permuted congruential generator (PCG). This family of pseudo-random number generators includes some that are "simultaneously extremely fast, extremely statistically good, and extremely space efficient" (O'Neill, 2014). Here, we use the PCG32 algorithm.

    This class is a descendant of the Random class. An instance of this class is used to generate a stream of pseudo-random numbers. The main differences are:

    • PCG algorithm is used; in particular, this is a port of the minimal C implementation.
    • Instances of Pcg32 are not thread-safe and so it doesn't obey the Random contract.
    Author:
    Ian Davies - Dec 6, 2018

      • Pcg32

        public Pcg32​(long initState,
             long initSeq)
        Creates a new random number generator using a long seed and a long stream number.

        The invocation new Pcg32(initState,initSeq) is equivalent to: 

          Pcg32 rnd = new Pcg32();
  rnd.seed(initState, initSeq);

      • nextInt

        public int nextInt()
        Returns the next pseudo-random, approximately uniformly distributed int value from this random number generator's sequence. The general contract of nextInt is that one int value is pseudo-randomly generated and returned. All 232 possible int values are produced with (approximately) equal probability.

      • seed

        public void seed()
        Initializes the generator with current time as the state and a (very likely to be) unique stream number. This ensures that even if multiple generators are initialized using this method while System.nanoTime() returns the same time, they will have different sequences.
